[normal]CORD UK; Tucker McCravy, CORD UK; Shihab Uddin Ahamad, ActionAid Myanmar; Dan Collison; Save the Children 
[normal]gave evidence.  
[normal]Q1 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Good afternoon and welcome.  Thank you very much for coming in to share your experiences of 
[normal]Burma
[normal] and your thoughts about where it might be heading.  As you know, the Committee is heading out there next week, and two of us have actually been out with the Speaker’s group in July.  We are looking at democracy and development, and the link between the two, given the way things have changed.  I just wondered, first of all, for the record, if you could introduce yourselves and your organisation.  
[normal]Shihab Uddin Ahamad[bold]: My name is Shihab.  I am the Country Director from ActionAid 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal], and I have been living in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] for the last seven years.
[normal]Brian Wakley[bold]: My name is Brian Wakley and I am the Chief Executive for Cord.
[normal]Tucker McCravy[bold]: My name is Tucker McCravy, and I am the Regional Programme Manager for Peacebuilding in the Cord Asia region.
[normal]Dan Collison[bold]: I am Dan Collison.  I work for Save the Children.  I am the Head of Programme Support for Save the Children International in 
[normal]London
[normal] here, but I lived and worked in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal], in 
[normal]Burma
[normal], between 2008 and 2011, originally managing the response to Cyclone Nargis.
[normal]Chris White:[bold] Before we start, can I just, for the record, express an interest?  I had a relationship with Cord, having visited 
[normal]Chad
[normal] with Cord before I became an MP.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] On the basis of what you said, we are perfectly relaxed, as far as I can see, about “
[normal]Burma
[normal]” and “
[normal]Myanmar
[normal]”.  They are becoming increasingly interchangeable, but we know there are some sensitivities there.  As I say, thank you for coming in.  We obviously see 
[normal]Burma
[normal] as being in a unique position, I suppose, after 50 years of being repressed, shut in and no development, top
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]down but opening up, which 
[normal]possibly offers 
[normal]great potential for the people but also 
[normal]carries 
[normal]a huge amount of risk.  Perhaps the thing to do really is to ask you to give us your thoughts at the moment.  What is your view?  Briefly, all of you, what is your take on the current situation?  How do you think it is going and what do you think are the key challenges?  If you are able to
[normal] offer 
[normal]a few key points 
[normal]in answer 
[normal]that would be helpful.
[normal]Dan Collison[bold]: You are right: it is a period of unprecedented and unforeseen change.  If I compare my experience when arriving in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] in 2008, there was a situation of fear and oppression that pervaded the country at the time, and things have changed dramatically.  There are lots and lots of reasons for that change, and we do not necessarily want to spend time exploring them now, although we could do, but there is good stuff happening, really profound change—the relaxation of censorship laws, the currency flotation, the tender of telecoms, the ceasefires.  For Save the Children, there is even what might seem like small stuff—the raising of the age of juveniles from 16 to 18.  There is lots of stuff going on; these changes are meaningful but fragile.  
[normal]One of the reasons for that is that the institutions in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] remain so weak—the parliament, the administration and the courts—and these changes are not necessarily being felt in people’s lives yet.  While you have big economic change happening at policy level, the everyday person is seeing massive hikes in electricity costs, food prices going up of course and the very serious inter
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]communal anti
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]Muslim violence that you have seen in recent months.  These are threats to stability, but it is fair to say that 
[normal]in terms of 
[normal]the changes we have seen over the last two years, I do not know about anybody else, but very few people saw them coming, if anybody.  We think that, despite these threats, the changes are hopefully largely irreversible.
[normal]Tucker McCravy[bold]: Just to echo what my colleague has said, there are unprecedented opportunities right now in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] for building a peaceful and democratic society.  There are a number of concurrent change processes that are happening, which make it quite challenging for both the leadership of the country, as well as 
[normal]the 
[normal]international donors and actors to engage in.  One 
[normal]change 
[normal]is the move from an autocratic style of leadership to one that is more democratic
[normal];
[normal] 
[normal]another 
[normal]is the move from more state
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]controlled and more closed economies to an open
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]market economy.  The third one, which is something that greatly interests us, is the movement from an ethically or religiously divided society into one that embraces the principles of pluralism.  
[normal]If we had to name perhaps the greatest challenge, the recent religious violence, the recent spates of attacks against Muslims, represents the single greatest challenge to 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal], because it could be the thread that unravels the entire ball of yarn, so to speak, in the democratic reform process.  With the international community in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] in the spotlight and the processes moving forward in a very positive way, this could be something that, if not directly and concisely addressed by the leadership, could undo a lot of the positive changes.  There is the larger question of what the role of the military is in either supporting or, in some 
[normal]ways, implicitly opposing these changes.  The larger processes of state
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]building and folding the democratic process towards democracy and development into the project of building a peaceful, sustainable and just society in Myanmar is the greatest challenge that we are facing right now.
[normal]Shihab Uddin Ahamad[bold]: I fully endorse both my colleagues.  I want to add that, because of these 50 or 60 years, they never had a chance to understand what democracy is and what human rights are.  The understanding of democracy and human rights of the 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] leaders and the people are very different from what we understand.  The people, the majority of wh
[normal]om
[normal] are Burmese, do not believe that other ethnic groups or people with different religious identities have the same rights.  A change in the Government is not enough.  Working on that is not enough.  That is what I see as the major challenge for development, bringing a culture of democracy and for peace.  
[normal]              
[normal]The second challenge
[normal] at the moment is that 
[normal]although Burma’s Government is very keen, particularly at the leadership level, for reform, the real capacity within the Burmese Government and their leaders to take this 
[normal]process 
[normal]forward alone is probably not enough.  Then the question is how far the international community will intervene and engage without taking the leadership role and letting the
[normal] Burmese Government 
[normal]lead the process.  
[normal]The other one is the issue of economic development, particularly what kind of model of economic development we will propose and participate in with them.  That is probably one of the major issues at this moment.  
[normal]Those are 
[normal]the main challenges.
[normal]Chair:[bold] Thank you very much.  Obviously our Committee has a particular responsibility to look at DFID’s operation, its potential and its strategy, so we have a number of questions on that.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Fiona Bruce:[bold] Thank you very much for outlining the main challenges that you sense at the moment.  My question really is: which of these do you think DFID is particularly specialised to assist with?  We would like your comment on the statement that DFID has made that it has taken a “high cost, high risk but also high return” approach to 
[normal]Burma
[normal].  Do you think this is the case and do you think it is the correct approach?
[normal]Shihab Uddin Ahamad[bold]: The UK Government probably has the longest history of engagement with 
[normal]Burma
[normal].  Even DFID’s team was pretty new when they started sometime in 2009 or 2010, but even the 
[normal]Bangkok
[normal] team had very good engagement with the different actors.  Currently
[normal],
[normal] probably the largest team of any donor is DFID.  They understand very well the DNA of the society, the pulse of the people and, at the same time, they are playing a leadership role at this moment with other donors, particularly since Cyclone Nargis.  I would say that DFID is in a good place to take the lead role in development.  That is their advantage.
[normal]              
[normal]Another advantage I see is that DFID’s approach to engaging with development actors is 
[normal]flexible 
[normal]compared 
[normal]with that of 
[normal]many other donors, most of whose aid is very tight.  DFID is flexible in terms of different approaches and interventions.  The third 
[normal]advantage 
[normal]is the DFID’s team understanding and the way they engage with civil society.  That puts them in a very good place for international relations with local society and, at the same time, the political society.  They are quite engaged and they understand the political society and politics of 
[normal]Burma
[normal].  
[normal]Tucker McCravy[bold]: I concur with my colleague.  DFID globally has significant expertise in state
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]building and, in particular, a very clear strategy 
[normal]on
[normal] building peaceful states and societies, which looks at a number of key areas that are germane to the situation in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal].  They are: 
[normal]trying to address the root causes of conflict; building in conflict resolution mechanisms; looking at how to contribute to sustainable political settlements; and also building capable, accountable and responsive governments.  That is a theme that has come up and will come up, again and again.  
[normal]I agree with my colleague that DFID has a particular stature in the 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] context, because it is one of the largest, if not the largest, bilateral donor and also because of its relations with the Government, both in terms of political society and civil society.  They are well placed both 
[normal]to 
[normal]engage with civil society to continue to develop civil society, 
[normal]and 
[normal]to strengthen government at the same time and, more importantly, to put those two development partners in dialogue with one another, because any sustainable democratic process or any sustainable process of resolution of grievances 
[normal]will 
[normal]involve the need to bring both of those actors to the table.  Using their long experience in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] and using the global framework of their state
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]building strategy makes them very well placed to address a number of the challenges
[normal] that we outlined in answer to 
[normal]the first question.  
[normal]Dan Collison[bold]: Aid flows to 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] are still relatively small, particularly in comparison 
[normal]with 
[normal]some of its neighbouring countries.  
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] receives about $10 per capita in aid support, which is about 20% of the aid on offer to 
[normal]Cambodia
[normal].  I am not saying that 
[normal]Cambodia
[normal] is a great example because, as we were discussing on the way in, perhaps when we come to the later part of the question about “What next?” or, a generation on from now, how aid will look, I do not think that any of us would think that where Cambodia is at presents a very good model in terms of aid dependency.  
[normal]There are a lot of tempting opportunities for a donor like DFID now, during this period of change.  Do you focus on education, micro
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]finance, parliamentary reform or parliamentary support and capacity-building?  Aid flows might increase a bit, but perhaps not dramatically.  It is really the international financial institutions 
[normal]such as 
[normal]the World Bank that are going to be big financiers of growth over the next few years.  Agencies like DFID can really play a strong role in influencing how those big IFIs go about their business in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal].
[normal]              
[normal]In terms of what DFID might usefully focus on, and indeed has been 
[normal]doing 
[normal]for a number of years, on the one hand, there is clear need and opportunity to invest in the supply side of service provision.  The health service and the education services are at a very low ebb.  Whether it is investing in township
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]level hardware, facility
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]level support or what you could call the software—the training and capacity-building of teachers and community health workers—that is a big job that the international community can and does support.
[normal]              
[normal]The other thing that we have not really mentioned yet is the incredibly high levels of rural poverty in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal], and what the aid effort and agencies like DFID can do to try to tackle some of that.  Per capita income, relative to its neighbours, is tiny.  Per capita income in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] is 6.3% of what it is in 
[normal]Thailand
[normal], so the discrepancies around the region are very stark.  
[normal]One thing that perhaps DFID could focus on, and has been 
[normal]doing 
[normal]through its contributions to the Livelihoods multi
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]donor fund, which is LIFT as you know, is around access to financial services for the poorest, trying to break the very damaging cycles of debt and credit that characterise most people’s lives in rural Myanmar, where the landless poor do not have access to credit, rely very much on debt or mortgaging their labour to get them through the agricultural season.  The two need to go together; there is no point in increasing people’s incomes so that they can access services that are still so poor.  
[normal]In terms of the risk and return, I like what my colleagues have been saying; the investments in building civil society are a bit unknown.  They are potentially risky because you 
[normal]do not quite know what you are going to spark off, but that is where the really creative aid assistance can be made in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] over the next few years.  If we get on to it, we have some fabulous examples of how that can contribute, not only to development but also to democratisation, as people get active, get engaged and get information.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q4 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hugh Bayley:[bold] Let me just follow up to Dan Collison first.  We were in 
[normal]Pakistan
[normal] not to
[normal]o
[normal] long ago and 
[normal]were 
[normal]horrified to see the impact that debt bondage has on people.  You were just talking about bonded labour.  In what 
[normal]sectors 
[normal]is this a particular problem?  Which NGOs and/or state development agencies have been trying to address these problems?
[normal]Dan Collison[bold]: It is a problem for the landless poor.  It is also a problem for small producers, because financial services are so poorly developed, and access to credit, through even the rudimentary banking system, is either very difficult or lending rates are so very high.  It means, on the one hand, small producers cannot get credit to grow their businesses and, therefore, employ the masses of landless labourers.  The landless labourers, as I said, mortgage their labour for rice farming, fishing rights and that sort of thing ahead of time, and are constantly repaying that to their landowners.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q5 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hugh Bayley:[bold] Who are their champions, if you wanted to break that cycle of indebtedness?
[normal]Dan Collison[bold]: In terms of the donor and aid community, the LIFT multi
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]donor fund, of which DFID is a major contributor, has been set up with an eye to trying to do something at scale about these problems of livelihoods and income poverty, predominantly in rural areas, but looking at rural areas in many of the ethnic minority areas as well.  There is good experience and lots to build on in two areas.  One is around improving access to micro
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]finance.  There has been very mixed experience with micro
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]finance in other parts of the world, but access to credit is so poor in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] at the moment that, where micro
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]finance has taken root, it is a very valued and valuable service.  Working out the details of how that is managed effectively and sustainably is a big challenge, but it is high on the agenda for the multi
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]donor LIFT consortium.
[normal]              
[normal]The other one worth considering, which is more problematic in terms of sustainability, but very effective in terms of helping people to get a leg up out of poverty, are cash transfers, which are essentially social protection mechanisms.  They are costly but we have seen, even in the recovery from Cyclone Nargis that, given a bit of cash support, families can quickly either rebuild and/or enhance their productive assets, so that it actually does lift them further out of poverty.  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q6 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Fiona O'Donnell:[bold] Can I just quickly come in, Dan, and ask if anyone else has anything to add?  Could you say a bit about the impact of climate change on rural poverty, and what the capacity is in 
[normal]Burma
[normal] to tackle the effects?
[normal]Dan Collison[bold]: I will have a go, just because clearly the country is prone to extreme climate events.  Nargis was one.  There were other strong cyclones afterwards.  Cyclone Giri destroyed parts of Rakhine state.  I do not have the science in front of me at all.  You might be able to have a go at that, 
[normal]Shihab, 
[normal]seeing as you are on the ground.  
[normal]Shihab Uddin Ahamad[bold]: I could bring or at least send a publication about the climate change impact.  I would be very happy to forward that to my colleagues.  It is very clear, in the article I was writing, that our focus on 
[normal]Burma
[normal] is more about the political issues, but the thing is we did not notice how much this country has been impacted by climate change.  The simple logic 
[normal]is it is a neighbour country of 
[normal]Bangladesh
[normal].  If 
[normal]Bangladesh
[normal] has that level of climate change impact, why not 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal]?  
[normal]The difference between the climate change impact in 
[normal]Burma
[normal] and 
[normal]Bangladesh
[normal] is that, in 
[normal]Bangladesh
[normal], the main area of impact is the coastal belt but, in 
[normal]Burma
[normal], it is the big three regions in the middle part, which are serially affected by drought.  If you look at the story of poverty that the UNDP research 
[normal]reveals, 
[normal]a huge concentration of food poverty is in the middle part of Burma—those three states—and 
[normal]that 
[normal]is because of that drought.  
[normal]We had huge investment, although not many other NGOs gave investment to the middle part of Burma, because girls are being trafficked to the neighbouring countries to the border of China and Thailand, because there is no way they could manage their food, because they have no agricultural production and no water.  Children cannot go to school because they have to go three or four kilometres away just to collect drinking water.  This is 
[normal]one aspect that we did not no
[normal]tice much about Burma
[normal], but we 
[normal]have documented these things recently through our research and photographs, and we are requesting that partner organisations that do a lot of work on climate change should look at that research.  DFID could take a leading role here but, unfortunately, 
[normal]according to 
[normal]DFID’s operational strategy
[normal],
[normal] they are not concentrating on climate change.
[normal]Chair:[bold] We will discuss that with them, but obviously they will tend to say that they cannot do everything.  That is where Hugh Bayley’s question about co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination might be relevant, so back to Hugh.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q7 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Hugh Bayley:[bold] The circumstances have changed rapidly in 
[normal]Burma
[normal] and now there are many, many donors rushing to respond to needs, so can you say something about how big a problem donor co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination is and whether there are things DFID could do to get better and more efficient use of resources, through better co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination?
[normal]Shihab Uddin Ahamad[bold]: From my experience on the ground, I can tell that most of the aid agencies, for some unknown reason, do not like co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination.  They want to go their own way.  DFID is probably the only organisation, 
[normal]along 
[normal]with AusAID
[normal],
[normal] that appreciates or participates in co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination.  
[normal]China
[normal], 
[normal]Japan
[normal] and 
[normal]India
[normal] are three donors that do not want to 
[normal]attend 
[normal]co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination meetings at all, but the European Union, DFID, AusAID, the Swiss Government, Swedish Government, Danish Government and Norwegian Government 
[normal]opt for 
[normal]co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination.  
[normal]This is very important, particularly in the current situation where we are expecting that many aid agencies will be able to engage with the Government, 
[normal]but to 
[normal]engage with the Government we 
[normal]particularly 
[normal]need co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination.  Who is contributing 
[normal]to 
[normal]which part?  
[normal]In particular, to introduce 
[normal]a strong accountability system, we need co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination, and I can see that DFID is in a very good position to co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordinate that.
[normal]Tucker McCravy[bold]: I would like to broaden the question a little bit, and look at the question of aid effectiveness generally speaking, of which co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination is one part.  If you look at the Paris Principles and the Busan Principles, they look at things 
[normal]such as 
[normal]how much aid matches the priorities of the host-country Government and how much ownership there is of the aid intervention that is taking place.  These are all considerations that are relevant to the 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] context.  
[normal]When we look at, for example, some of the ill effects of 
[normal]the 
[normal]lack of co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination, some of the principles of “do no harm” with aid effectiveness apply.  If you have duplication of efforts or if you have, in some cases, aid in humanitarian situations which, by virtue of the particular group to which resources are being given, actually creates or engenders further conflict, then that 
[normal]is 
[normal]part of the co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination question.  
[normal]A
[normal]s my colleague has mentioned, 
[normal]you also have to consider 
[normal]the logistical ability of the Government to entertain so many donors that come in with requests or even international organisations that come in with requests for meetings or requests for scoping missions, or just general visits to the Government
[normal].  That leads to 
[normal]what is called a problem with absorptive capacity.  There is simply no time for the Government to engage and effectively pass policy discussions, in planning and formulation, when they are entertaining so many people who are coming to offer their good will and good services.  
[normal]That seconds what my colleague was saying
[normal].  If 
[normal]co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination is not properly done and if it does not harmonise with the needs of the host
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]country Government, in a broader framework of effectiveness, then consideration of “do no harm” 
[normal]principles 
[normal]appl
[normal]ies.  That is a very i
[normal]mportant 
[normal]consideration 
[normal]as well.
[normal]Dan Collison[bold]: The instruments of multi
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]donor funds do present quite a good means for co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination, and there were quite a number of them at work in Myanmar well: the Global Fund for HIV, TB and malaria; the one we have mentioned, LIFT, the Livelihoods donor fund; the three diseases or the 3MDG fund for health, which is quite new; and then the one that Save the Children is helping to implement, which is the Myanmar Education Consortium.  As I said, DFID has invested heavily in all of these.  
[normal]They 
[normal]represent 
[normal]good co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination mechanisms
[normal], because t
[normal]hey reduce transaction costs
[normal] and they 
[normal]give a broad group of partners, donors and NGOs a common advocacy platform.  Rather than, as Tucker said, the Government being assailed by lots of different voices with well-meaning advice, they give a chance for the aid actors to co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordinate and streamline their messaging and their approaches to government, based on the evidence of what is working.  Those can be a very good co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]ordination mechanism.  
[normal]Although s
[normal]ome of them are quite high
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]cost to run
[normal], they 
[normal]certainly reduce transaction costs for the donors
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q8 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chris White:[bold] This is really for Save the Children.  I would be interested, perhaps not at this time, to understand your comments regarding micro
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]finance—countries where you think it has worked and countries where you think it has not worked.  Generally
[normal], 
[normal]in the Committee’s experience, 
[normal]in 
[normal]the countries where we 
[normal]have 
[normal]see
[normal]n
[normal] these very small projects
[normal], they 
[normal]have been quite successful, so it would be interesting to hear your views.  
[normal]I am directing this question to you first
[normal], Dan,
[normal] as you have argued that DFID should be doing more in terms of education in Burma
[normal], but anybody else who wants to, pick up
[normal].  Do you think it should be a higher priority, and do you think its contribution to the multi
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]donor education fund is sufficient?
[normal]Dan Collison[bold]: I do think it should be a higher priority but, of course, that is a difficult thing to say when earlier I said DFID has to be realistic and prioritise.  There are so many things on the table that one could put one’s support behind.  
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] has a young population.  This is an opportunity to invest in the next generation, and well
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]targeted aid can make a difference to many different facets of education, not just basic education—that means government
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]provided education, which traditionally NGOs have had a difficult time getting 
[normal]to grips with, because the Government has preferred to work with UNICEF on that front—but around formal monastic pre
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]school, and what we call ECCD: early-years childhood care and development.  There is very important investment in helping children get to grips with learning early on.  They can get to grips with learning in their mother tongue early on.  
[normal]This period of ceasefire reconciliation is 
[normal]offering 
[normal]a whole new set of opportunities to think about curriculum development in 
[normal]the 
[normal]mother tongue, and how you link the needs for children to learn in their mother tongue in early years with a necessity for a broad national curriculum in the national language.  The role that that can play in reconciliation and state
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]building is very powerful.  
[normal]Based on our experience of working in education and working in DFID, you can get very good results working to support teachers to move away from very uninspiring rote
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]learning techniques and harsh discipline to more of what we call child
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]centred ways of teaching, whereby children are encouraged to ask questions and be critical thinkers.  That is a very powerful way of getting kids to question the world around them and provides a whole different outlook from what this current generation has been brought up with.  We think there is a
[normal]n opportunity for
[normal] very powerful investment there, and this can create a strong platform for reconciliation and nation-building.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q9 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold]  In your submission, you made particular reference to the international community’s education programmes in the Karen regime.  Is that, first of all, only in that area?  They have not done it anywhere else.  You have said it has “increased the isolation of these populations”.
