[normal]Brian Wakley[bold]: Coming back to some of the points on critical thinking, learning and support for education, it is not just 
[normal]an issue 
[normal]at the primary and secondary
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]school level; one of the things we would support 
[normal]keenly in education is 
[normal]professionals helping Governments and local governments, whether through secondments or even 
[normal]by 
[normal]bringing people over across countries to experience different ways of working.  Part of the critical-thinking approach helps people to ask questions.  In a state where there has been 50 years of control, and people are taught and learn to think in order to be safe and secure, the challenge, as things open up, is trying to encourage that critical reflection, that questioning, that imagining of a different state and of a different space.  
[normal]One of things that Cord has done with its partners in different countries is 
[normal]to encourage 
[normal]this learning approach, where you get peer groups working together; you will 
[normal]then 
[normal]get different sectors, whether it is government and civil society leaders, thinking about what leadership looks like and asking those questions of how we want things to be.  
[normal]              
[normal]As part of that, on this question of education and the secular approach, I would possibly differ slightly from my colleague, in that there is a lot from a faith
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]based approach that is very strong
[normal]ly tied 
[normal]with people’s identity, history and where they are linked to.  
