[normal]Tucker McCravy[bold]: 
[normal]On education, 
[normal]I concur with what Brian is saying.  I think some of the approaches that could and should be taken, and that DFID could think about sponsoring, 
[normal]relate to 
[normal]civic education.  The notion of the work that our colleagues at Save the Children have been doing on more of a child
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]centred approach to learning—the critical thinking encouraging reflection—
[normal]means that 
[normal]ultimately, aside from being a social good in and of itself, the spillover or the benefit is 
[normal]that 
[normal]it creates citizens who are more able to ask questions, who are more able to challenge the authority of the local government, to engage with the authority of the local government or, in some sense, to ask themselves questions about what it means to be Burmese: “What are my civic rights?  What are my civic duties?”  Civic education sets the foundation or the groundwork for civic engagement and the idea that local communities can work with local government officials on issues that really matter, participating in decisions that affect their lives.
[normal]Another challenge to the democratic space opening up is that, in democracy, freedom of expression and freedom 
[normal]to say 
[normal]whatever you want is accepted, and is openly touted as something, freedom of speech, which is good.  
[normal]In terms of 
[normal]monastic education
[normal], the issue 
[normal]is not only formal education, but 
[normal]those 
[normal]movements that are spearheaded by ethno
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]religious national monks.  
[normal]The 
[normal]969 Movement in 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] promotes religious intolerance and says, “Muslims have no place in this country.  Buddhism is the religion of the state, so we need to actuate that in policy.”  There have been some moves by the President to nip that in the bud and say that is unacceptable in a society that is promoting pluralism and tolerance of values.  Th
[normal]at
[normal] is something we need to instil at every educational level, not only at the adult-learning level, but at the formal and informal education level.  
[normal]We have an opportunity and DFID has an opportunity to learn from the lessons of, for example, 
[normal]Sri Lanka
[normal], in looking at how peace education or civic education can be integrated into the curriculum.  In the case of the conflict there, the Sinhalese, the Tamils and the Muslims are really learning how to co
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]exist, how to think of themselves all as not only just part of their ethnic groups or religious groups, but 
[normal]as 
[normal]part of a larger identity.  
[normal]That is crucial now, 
[normal]because it is a generational process.  The children who you are raising now will be the future leaders of the country.  If you are raising them with values of intolerance or 
[normal]a 
[normal]lack of ability to see their own role in civic engagement, in 30 years from now, you will see that those are the people who run the country. 
[normal]              
[normal]Linked to that is this question of 
[normal]what 
[normal]you focus on 
[normal]in 
[normal]education.  Obviously it is very clear that you need to focus on basic education—primary and secondary education.  There is also a strong argument, and I think Save the Children is doing some work in this area, 
[normal]for 
[normal]looking at 
[normal]the capacity and expertise in 
[normal]tertiary education in the universities, looking at the diaspora and the talent that exists abroad, the former political prisoners who were ousted during the rule of military dictatorship, and 
[normal]at 
[normal]what role and what capacity they have to 
[normal]shape the 
[normal]future 
[normal]development of the country.  Sometimes when we think about education, we think, rightly so, about access to quality education at the primary level
[normal], but we should take 
[normal]a broader view of it and think about civic education, peace education and education that may consider, for example, funding scholarships for bright Myanmar students to go aboard and study public policy, in England or the United States, and then 
[normal]to 
[normal]come back and 
[normal]act as 
[normal]contributing members of this reform policy.  
[normal]              
[normal]Lastly, 
[normal]we should avoid the mistakes of 
[normal]Cambodia
[normal], where civil society has stepped in and has provided a large role as service providers of both education and health.  It has done that very well and is playing a really major role in service delivery, which arguably is the role of the state.  The more we do that, the more we empower civil society.  We have to be conscious and 
[normal]aware 
[normal]of the fact that we really need to be building the capacity of the state to deliver the goods of education or to be the duty bearers, in some sense, to their population.  If civil society is always fulfilling that role, it links to another one of the questions of the Committee, which is: will 
[normal]Myanmar
[normal] ever graduate from aid in a generation?  If the state is actually not being held accountable to fulfil some of those functions, the answer to the question becomes no.
